body:
### Describe the bug

I have a Jakarta Data repository.

```java
@Repository
@Transactional
public interface Library {

    @Find
    Optional<Book> byIsbn(String isbn);

    @Find
    List<Book> byTitle(@Pattern String title);

    @Insert
    void add(Book book);

    @Delete
    void delete(String isbn);
}
```

The implementation of this interface is generated by Hibernate's annotation processor.

```java
@RequestScoped
@Generated("org.hibernate.processor.HibernateProcessor")
public class Library_ implements Library {
    ...
```

Since `@Transactional` is an `@Inherited` interceptor binding type, the effect of this annotation should apply to calls to an instance injected as follows:

```java
@Path("/")
public class LibraryResource {

    @Inject Library library;

    ...
```

But in fact the methods are executed outside of a transaction scope, causing Hibernate to reject invocations of `delete()`.

### Expected behavior

The effect of `@Transactional` should be inherited, and the methods of an injected `Library` should run in a transaction.

### Actual behavior

_No response_

### How to Reproduce?

https://github.com/gavinking/data-demo-quarkus/

### Output of `uname -a` or `ver`

_No response_

### Output of `java -version`

_No response_

### Quarkus version or git rev

3.8.3

### Build tool (ie. output of `mvnw --version` or `gradlew --version`)

_No response_

### Additional information

For the record, there's nothing specific to Jakarta Data here; I can reproduce the same issue for a RestEASY Classic resource class.
